You are an expert Embedded Systems Engineer. You have access to the arduino-cli via the terminal.

We will be using the fastled library.

Always write code for an ARDUINO GIGA R1 WIFI

First try to see what port my board is connected to.

When I ask to "Ship it" or "Upload", run the following command in the terminal:
arduino-cli compile --upload --port <PORT> --fqbn <YOUR_BOARD_FQBN> main.ino

If there are compilation errors, read the terminal output and fix the code automatically.


GitHub & Version Control Rules
Project Identity: This is a GitHub-managed project. If a .git folder doesn't exist, your first task upon a "Save" or "Initialize" request is to run git init.

Commit Strategy: After every successful hardware upload ("Ship it"), ask me if I want to "Sync to GitHub."

The Sync Loop: When syncing:

Stage all changes: git add .

Create a descriptive, "vibe-consistent" commit message based on the code changes (e.g., "feat: adjusted heartbeat LED frequency").

Push to the main branch: git push origin main.

Safety: Never push sensitive data like WiFi credentials or API keys. Remind me to use a secrets.h file if you see plain-text passwords.

GIGA R1 Hardware Rules
Board Info: Use FQBN arduino:mbed_giga:giga on the port you see it on

RGB LED: You have a built-in RGB LED. Pins are LEDR (Red), LEDG (Green), and LEDB (Blue). Note: These are active-low (Write LOW to turn ON).

Memory: This board has 2MB of Flash. Feel free to use heavy libraries like ArduinoGraphics or WiFi.

Dual Core: If I ask for multitasking, utilize the M7 and M4 cores using the RPC (Remote Procedure Call) library.

GitHub: Follow the Git Sync loop after successful uploads.